                <head>15. Editorial Note</head>
                <p>Between June 23 and July 15, the United States and the Soviet Union exchanged a
                    series of notes and aides-mémoire regarding demonstrations outside the Soviet
                    Mission at the United Nations on June 19, 21, and 22. The Soviet Government
                    contended that U.S. authorities had taken inadequate measures to protect the
                    Mission, alleged that New York City police had incited the picketers, and
                    eventually demanded that the United States pay for property damage that occurred
                    during the June 21 and 22 incidents. The United States denied complicity with
                    the protesters or official negligence in protecting the Mission and refused
                    liability for the damages, but agreed to consider an exgratia payment to cover
                    them. For text of the June 23 Soviet note to the U.S. Mission at the United
                    Nations, see Department of State <hi rend="italic">Bulletin</hi>, July 14, 1958,
                    page 50. U.S. aide-mémoire 59, delivered to the Soviet Foreign Office on July
                    15, is in Department of State, Central Files, 310.361/7–458.</p>
            </div>
